ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.FormAndInfoAndMaterialsTxt: MOST OF THE FOUNDATION'S GRANTS ARE MADE THROUGH NATIONAL PROGRAMS ESTABLISHED TO ADDRESS SPECIFIC ISSUES IN HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE. THESE ISSUES AND FIELDS OF INTEREST ARE DESCRIBED ON THE FOUNDATION'S INTERNET SITE (WWW.RWJF.ORG). THE COMPETITIVE GRANT APPLICATION PROCESS FOR NATIONAL PROGRAMS BEGINS WITH A "CALL FOR PROPOSAL," WHICH CAN BE FOUND ON THE FOUNDATION'S INTERNET SITE. THE FOUNDATION ALSO AWARDS GRANTS OUTSIDE OF ITS NATIONAL PROGRAMS THAT MAY BE UNSOLICITED OR SOLICITED BY THE FOUNDATION, BUT THAT GENERALLY FIT THE FOUNDATION'S EXPLICIT FIELDS OF INTEREST WITHIN HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE. APPLICANTS MAY INITIATE THE GRANT PROCESS BY SUBMITTING A THREE-PAGE, ELECTRONIC BRIEF PROPOSAL USING THE APPLICATION FORM PROVIDED ON-LINE.
ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.SubmissionDeadlinesTxt: NO DEADLINES, EXCEPT WHEN FOUNDATION ISSUES A CALL FOR PROPOSAL (CFP). EACH CFP SPECIFIES THE TIMETA
ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.RestrictionsOnAwardsTxt: THE ROBERT WOOD JOHNSON FOUNDATION'S MISSION IS TO IMPROVE THE HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE OF ALL AMERICANS. TO HELP AMERICANS LEAD HEALTHIER LIVES AND GET THE CARE THEY NEED, THE FOUNDATION MAKES GRANTS TO IDENTIFY AND PURSUE NEW OPPORTUNITIES TO ADDRESS PERSISTENT HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE CHALLENGES AND TO ANTICIPATE AND RESPOND TO EMERGING CHALLENGES. THE FOUNDATION FOCUSES THE MAJORITY OF ITS GRANT MAKING IN FOUR PORTFOLIOS, OR FIELDS. FOR A PROJECT TO BE ELIGIBLE FOR SUPPORT, IT MUST SUCCESSFULLY ADDRESS THE OBJECTIVES OF ONE OF THESE PORTFOLIOS AS FOLLOWS: 1. TARGETED: ADDRESSING SPECIFIC IMPROVEMENTS IN TARGETED HEALTH AND HEALTH CARE CHALLENGES OVER A DEFINED TIME PERIOD. CURRENT TARGETED FIELDS INCLUDE: HEALTH CARE COVERAGE, QUALITY/EQUALITY OF CARE, CHILDHOOD OBESITY AND PUBLIC HEALTH. 2. BUILDING HUMAN CAPITAL: FOSTERING EXCELLENCE AMONG A DIVERSE GROUP OF SCHOLARS AND PROFESSIONALS THROUGH LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT, TRAINING AND RESEARCH TO ENSURE THAT OUR NATION HAS A SUFFICIENT, WE

GeneralExplanationGrp.MediumExplanationTxt: Childhood Obesity - Programs that help to reverse the epidemic of childhood obesity by 2015, particularly among children and families at greatest risk, by improving and promoting access to affordable healthy foods and increasing opportunities for physical activity in schools and communities ($5,310,984). General Outreach and Support - Programs which support improving health care value, promoting prevention, growing the field of health and health care leadership, supporting communications and policy projects, and synthesizing and spreading research and evaluation findings through the web, social media and other means ($6,216,100). Building Human Capital - Programs and activities to prepare health professionals for leadership; train scholars to conduct health policy and systems research; encourage youth to pursue health careers; enhance the skills and careers of frontline health workers; and promote diversity in the health workforce to serve the needs of a changing population. Includes programs to improve patient care and community health by reinforcing the role of nurses in hospital and ambulatory settings and in public health systems; to increase and improve inter-professional collaboration between nurses and other health professionals; reduce the nationwide nursing shortage and increase production of nursing faculty to meet growing demands for well-trained nurses ($6,450,989). Improving Health and Health Care for Vulnerable Populations - Programs to promote, spread and sustain new and promising approaches to meet the health needs of low-income communities, that cut across multiple service systems and that develop and replicate successful models that address poor health status in the context of factors such as education, housing, poverty and the physical environment ($7,042,923). Other Targeted Programs - Nationwide programs to revitalize public health systems, services and policies that protect, promote, and preserve the health of all Americans; to improve the quality of health care; to help provide effective, affordable health insurance coverage for all Americans, to create and promote innovations that may result in solutions at the cutting edge of health and health care; and to support locally-based projects that promote the health and health care of New Jerseyans($22,366,721). Total Direct Charitable Activities Expenses: $47,387,717
